the experiments have been better designed or analyzed? These are some of the questions addressed by the contributors to this volume, the result of a conference on social experimentation sponsored in 1981 by the National Bureau of Economic Research. The first section of the book looks at four types of experiments and what each accomplished. Frank P. Stafford examines the negative income tax experiments, Dennis J. Aigner considers the experiments with electricity pricing based on time of use, Harvey S. Rosen evaluates housing allowance experiments, and Jeffrey E. Harris reports on health experiments. In the second section, addressing experimental design and analysis, Jerry A. Hausman and David A. Wise highlight the absence of random selection of participants in social experiments, Frederick Mosteller and Milton C. Weinstein look specifically at the design of medical experiments, and Ernst W. Stromsdorfer examines the effects of experiments on policy. Each chapter is followed by the commentary of one or more distinguished economists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAide de l'État au logementxCongrèsxÉvaluationxÉtats-Unis. 0aElectric utilitiesxCongressesxRatesxTime-of-use pricingxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aElectric utilitiesxRatesxTime-of-use pricingzUnited StatesxEvaluationvCongresses. 0aEvaluation research (Social action programs)vCongresses. 0aEvaluation research (Social action programs)xCongresses. 0aHousing subsidiesxCongressesxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aHousing subsidieszUnited StatesxEvaluationvCongresses. 0aImpôt négatif sur le revenuxÉvaluationxCongrèsxÉtats-Unis. 0aMedical policyxCongressesxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aMedical policyzUnited StatesxEvaluationvCongresses. 0aNegative income taxxCongressesxEvaluationxUnited States. 0aNegative income taxzUnited S